<div class="container">
    <h1>Interfaces in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>
        An <strong>interface</strong> is a contract that defines a set of methods and properties that a class must implement.  
        Interfaces allow you to achieve abstraction and simulate multiple inheritance in C#.  
        This is a more advanced concept, and we will revisit interfaces in the <strong>Advanced Web</strong> section to explore them in greater detail.
    </p>

    <h2>Example: Creating and Implementing an Interface</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Define an Interface</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public interface IVehicle
{
    void StartEngine();
    void StopEngine();
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Implement the Interface</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Car : IVehicle
{
    public void StartEngine()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Car engine started.");
    }

    public void StopEngine()
    {
        Console.WriteLine("Car engine stopped.");
    }
}

// Usage
IVehicle myCar = new Car();
myCar.StartEngine();
myCar.StopEngine();
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        In this example, the <strong>IVehicle</strong> interface defines the methods <strong>StartEngine</strong> and <strong>StopEngine</strong> without implementation.  
        The <strong>Car</strong> class implements the interface and provides the actual behavior for both methods.  
        When we call <code>myCar.StartEngine()</code> or <code>myCar.StopEngine()</code>, the corresponding method in the <strong>Car</strong> class executes.
    </p>
    <p><strong>Expected Output:</strong></p>
    <pre>
Car engine started.
Car engine stopped.
    </pre>

    <h2>Key Points About Interfaces</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>An interface contains only method and property signatures, not implementations.</li>
        <li>A class implementing an interface must provide implementations for all its members.</li>
        <li>Interfaces provide abstraction, which allows you to write flexible and maintainable code.</li>
        <li>A class can implement multiple interfaces, allowing a form of multiple inheritance.</li>
        <li>Interfaces are widely used in frameworks and design patterns to decouple code and increase flexibility.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        Note: Interfaces are a more complex topic in OOP. While this example gives a basic understanding, we will revisit and explore them in much greater depth in the <strong>Advanced Web</strong> section.
    </p>

